# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: macos-darwin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Darwin is mostly POSIX-compatible, but has never, by itself, been certified as compatible with any version of POSIX.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Starting with Leopard, macOS has been certified as compatible with the Single UNIX Specification version 3 (SUSv3).
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The heritage of Darwin began with Unix derivatives supplemented by aspects of NeXT's NeXTSTEP operating system (later, since version 4.0, known as OPENSTEP), first released in 1989.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] After Apple bought NeXT in 1996, it announced it would base its next operating system on OPENSTEP.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] This was developed into Rhapsody in 1997, Mac OS X Server 1.0 in 1999, Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000, and Mac OS X 10.0 in 2001.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] In 1999, Apple announced it would release the source code for the Mach 2.5 microkernel, BSD Unix 4.4 OS, and the Apache Web server components of Mac OS X Server.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] At the time, interim CEO Steve Jobs alluded to British naturalist Charles Darwin by announcing "because it's about evolution".
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] In 2000, the core operating system components of Mac OS X were released as open-source software under the Apple Public Source License (APSL) as Darwin; the higher-level components, such as the Cocoa and Carbon frameworks, remained closed-source.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Up to Darwin 8.0.1, released in April 2005, Apple released a binary installer (as an ISO image) after each major Mac OS X release that allowed one to install Darwin on PowerPC and Intel x86 systems as a standalone operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Minor updates were released as packages that were installed separately.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Darwin is now only available as source code.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] As of January 2023, Apple no longer mentions Darwin by name on its Open Source website and only publishes an incomplete collection of open-source projects relating to macOS and iOS.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The kernel of Darwin is XNU, a hybrid kernel which uses Open Software Foundation Mach Kernel (OSFMK) 7.3 from the OSF, various elements of FreeBSD (including the process model, network stack, and virtual file system), and an object-oriented device driver API called IOKit.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The hybrid kernel design provides the flexibility of a microkernel and the performance of a monolithic kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The last bootable full release of Darwin supported 32-bit and 64-bit Apple PowerPC systems and 32-bit Intel PCs.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] An open-source port of the XNU kernel exists that supports Darwin on Intel and AMD x86 platforms not officially supported by Apple, though it does not appear to have been updated since 2009.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] An open-source port of the XNU kernel also exists for ARM platforms, though it has not been updated since 2016.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Older versions supported some or all of 32-bit PowerPC, 64-bit PowerPC, 32-bit x86, and 32-bit ARM.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] It supports the POSIX API by way of its BSD lineage (largely FreeBSD userland), so a large number of programs written for various other UNIX-like systems can be compiled on Darwin with no changes to the source code.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Darwin does not include many of the defining elements of macOS, such as the Carbon and Cocoa APIs or the Quartz Compositor and Aqua user interface, and thus cannot run Mac applications.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] It does, however, support a number of lesser-known features of macOS, such as mDNSResponder, which is the multicast DNS responder and a core component of the Bonjour networking technology, and launchd, an advanced service management framework.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] In July 2003, Apple released Darwin under version 2.0 of the Apple Public Source License (APSL), which the Free Software Foundation (FSF) qualifies as a free software license.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The APSL is similar to AGPL, including in being incompatible with the GNU General Public License.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Previous versions of the APSL license did not meet the FSF definition of free software, although they did meet the requirements of the Open Source Definition.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The following is a table of major Darwin releases with their dates of release and their derivative operating system releases.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Note that the corresponding releases may have been released on a different date.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The jump in version numbers from Darwin 1.4.1 to 5.1 with the release of Mac OS X v10.1.1 was designed to tie Darwin to the Mac OS X version and build numbering system, which in turn is inherited from NeXTSTEP.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] In the build numbering system of macOS, every version has a unique beginning build number, which identifies what whole version of macOS it is part of.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Mac OS X v10.0 had build numbers starting with 4, 10.1 had build numbers starting with 5, and so forth (earlier build numbers represented developer releases).
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The command uname -r in Terminal will show the Darwin version number ("20.3.0"), and the command uname -v will show the XNU build version string, which includes the Darwin version number.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The command sw_vers will show the corresponding ProductName ("macOS"), the ProductVersion number ("11.2.3") and the BuildVersion string ("20D91").
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Due to the free software nature of Darwin, there have been projects that aim to modify the operating system or take Darwin’s parts for their own purpose.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Among these, DarwinBSD, OpenDarwin, and PureDarwin can be termed "alternative Darwin distributions" in a sense analogous to Linux distributions.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] OpenDarwin was a project to develop a community-led operating system based on the Darwin system.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] It was founded in April 2002 by Apple and Internet Systems Consortium.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Its goal was to increase collaboration between Apple developers and the free software community.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Apple benefited from the project because improvements to OpenDarwin would be incorporated into Darwin releases; and the free/open-source community benefited from being given complete control over its own operating system, which could then be used in free software distributions such as GNU-Darwin.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] On July 25, 2006, the OpenDarwin team announced that the project was shutting down, as they felt OpenDarwin had "become a mere hosting facility for Mac OS X related projects", and that the efforts to create a standalone Darwin operating system had failed.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] They also state: "Availability of sources, interaction with Apple representatives, difficulty building and tracking sources, and a lack of interest from the community have all contributed to this." The last stable release was version 7.2.1, released on July 16, 2004.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] PureDarwin is a project to create a bootable operating system image from Apple's released source code for Darwin.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Since the halt of OpenDarwin and the release of bootable images since Darwin 8.x, it has been increasingly difficult to create a full operating system as many components became closed source.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] In 2015 the project created a preview release based on Darwin 9 with an X11 GUI, followed by a command-line only 17.4 Beta based on Darwin 17 in 2019.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] ravynOS is a project to develop a Free and Open Source operating system that aims to be both source-compatible and eventually binary-compatible with Apple's macOS operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Although originally building upon a FreeBSD and NextBSD foundation, the lead dev, Zoë Knox, announced on October 28, 2025, that the operating system would be moving to a Darwin base.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] Since this change, work has been done on getting the legacy Darwin sources to build, as well as modernizing the build system and parts of the operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The following are not Darwin derivatives, at least not beyond the extent that any program written for an operating system is partly derived from its application programming interface and other constraints.
[src:macos-darwin/darwin-operating-system] The following projects re-implements parts of macOS API that are above the level of Darwin.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] GCD was first released with Mac OS X 10.6, and is also available with iOS 4 and above.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] The name "Grand Central Dispatch" is a reference to Grand Central Terminal.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] The source code for the library that provides the implementation of GCD's services, *libdispatch*, was released by Apple under the Apache License on September 10, 2009.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] It has been ported to FreeBSD 8.1+, MidnightBSD 0.3+, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] Attempts in 2011 to make libdispatch work on Windows were not merged into upstream.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] Apple has its own port of libdispatch.dll for Windows shipped with Safari and iTunes, but no SDK is provided.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] Since around 2017, the original libdispatch repository hosted by Nick Hutchinson was deprecated in favor of a version that is part of the Swift core library created in June 2016.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] The new version supports more platforms, notably including Windows.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] GCD works by allowing specific tasks in a program that can be run in parallel to be queued up for execution and, depending on availability of processing resources, scheduling them to execute on any of the available processor cores (referred to as "routing" by Apple).
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] A task can be expressed either as a function or as a "block." Blocks are an extension to the syntax of C, C++, and Objective-C programming languages that encapsulate code and data into a single object in a way similar to a closure.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] GCD can still be used in environments where blocks are not available.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] Grand Central Dispatch still uses threads at the low level but abstracts them away from the programmer, who will not need to be concerned with as many details.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] Tasks in GCD are lightweight to create and queue; Apple states that 15 instructions are required to queue up a work unit in GCD, while creating a traditional thread could easily require several hundred instructions.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] Libdispatch comes with its own object model, *OS Object*, that is partially compatible with the Objective-C model.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] As a result, its objects can be bridged *toll-free* to ObjC objects.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] GCD is used throughout macOS (beginning with 10.6 Snow Leopard), and Apple has encouraged its adoption by macOS application developers.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] His announcement observed that the GCD MPM had one third to half the number of lines as other threaded MPMs.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] GCD is implemented by libdispatch, with support from pthreads non-POSIX extensions developed by Apple.
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] Apple has changed the interface since its inception (in OS X 10.5) through the official launch of GCD (10.6), Mountain Lion (10.8) and Mavericks (10.9).
[src:macos-darwin/grand-central-dispatch] The latest changes involve making the code supporting pthreads, both in user mode and kernel, private (with kernel pthread support reduced to shims only, and the actual *workqueue* implementation moved to a separate kernel extension).
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The project at Carnegie Mellon ran from 1985 to 1994, ending with Mach 3.0, which is a true microkernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach was developed as a replacement for the kernel in the BSD version of Unix, not requiring a new operating system to be designed around it.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach and its derivatives exist within several commercial operating systems, including all those using the XNU operating system kernel, which incorporates an earlier non-microkernel version of Mach as a major component.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The Mach virtual memory management system was also adopted in 4.4BSD by the BSD developers at CSRG, and appears in modern BSD-derived Unix systems such as FreeBSD.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach is the logical successor to Carnegie Mellon's Accent kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach's lead developer Richard Rashid has been employed at Microsoft since 1991; he founded the Microsoft Research division.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Co-founding Mach developer Avie Tevanian was formerly head of software at NeXT, then Chief Software Technology Officer at Apple Inc. until March 2006.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The developers rode bicycles to lunch through rainy Pittsburgh's mud puddles, and Tevanian joked the word "muck" could form a backronym for their Multi-User (or Multiprocessor Universal) Communication Kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Italian CMU engineer Dario Giuse later asked project leader Rick Rashid about the project's current title and received "MUCK" as the answer, though not spelled out but just pronounced /mʌk/.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] According to the Italian alphabet, he wrote "Mach".
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Rashid liked Giuse's spelling "Mach" so much that it prevailed.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] A key concept in the original Unix operating system is the idea of a pipe.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] A pipe is an abstraction allowing data to be moved as an unstructured stream of bytes between programs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Using pipes, users can link together multiple programs to complete tasks, feeding data through several consecutive small programs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This contrasts with typical operating systems of the era, which require a single large program that can handle the entire task, or alternately, used files to pass data, which was resource-expensive and time-consuming.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Pipes were built on the underlying input/output system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This system is, in turn, based on a model where drivers are expected to periodically "block" while they wait for tasks to complete.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] For instance, a printer driver might send a line of text to a line printer and then have nothing to do until the printer completes printing that line.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In this case, the driver indicates that it was blocked, and the operating system allows some other program to run until the printer indicates it is ready for more data.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In the pipes system the limited resource was memory, and when one program filled the memory assigned to the pipe, it would naturally block.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Normally this would cause the consuming program to run, emptying the pipe again.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In contrast to a file, where the entire file has to be read or written before the next program can use it, pipes made the movement of data across multiple programs occur in a piecemeal fashion without any programmer intervention.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Implementing pipes in memory buffers forced data to be copied from program to program, a time-consuming and resource intensive operation.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This made the pipe concept unsuitable for tasks where quick turnaround or low latency was needed, such as in most device drivers.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The operating system's kernel and most core functionality was instead written in a single large program.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] When new functionality, such as computer networking, was added to the operating system, the size and complexity of the kernel grew, too.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Unix pipes offered a conceptual system that could be used to build arbitrarily complex solutions out of small cooperating programs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] These smaller programs were easier to develop and maintain, and had well-defined interfaces that simplified programming and debugging.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] These qualities are even more valuable for device drivers, where small size and bug-free performance was extremely important.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] There was a strong desire to model the kernel on the same basis of small cooperating programs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] One of the first systems to use a pipe-like system underpinning the operating system was the Aleph kernel developed at the University of Rochester.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This introduced the concept of ports, which were essentially a shared memory implementation.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In Aleph, the kernel was reduced to providing access to the hardware, including memory and the ports, while conventional programs using the ports system implemented all behavior, from device drivers to user programs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This concept greatly reduced the size of the kernel, and permitted users to experiment with different drivers simply by loading them and connecting them together at runtime.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This greatly eased the problems when developing new operating system code, which would otherwise require the machine to be restarted.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The overall concept of a small kernel and external drivers became known as a microkernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Aleph was implemented on Data General Eclipse minicomputers and was tightly bound to them.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This machine was far from ideal, since it required memory to be copied between programs, which resulted in considerable performance overhead.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Nevertheless, Aleph proved that the basic system was sound, and went on to demonstrate computer clustering by copying the memory over an early Ethernet interface.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Around this time a new generation of central processors (CPUs) were coming to market, offering a 32-bit address space and (initially optional) support for a memory management unit (MMU).
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The MMU handled the instructions needed to implement a virtual memory system by keeping track of which *pages* of memory were in use by various programs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This offered a new solution to the port concept, using the copy-on-write (COW) mechanism provided by the virtual memory system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Instead of copying data between programs, all that was required was to instruct the MMU to provide access to that same memory.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This system would implement the interprocess communications (IPC) system with dramatically higher performance.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This concept was picked up at Carnegie-Mellon, who adapted Aleph for the PERQ workstation and implemented it using copy-on-write.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The port was successful, but the resulting Accent kernel was of limited practical use because it did not run existing software.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Moreover, Accent was as tightly tied to PERQ as Aleph was to the Eclipse.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The major change between these experimental kernels and Mach was the decision to make a version of the existing 4.2BSD kernel re-implemented on the Accent message-passing concepts.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Such a kernel would be binary compatible with existing BSD software, making the system immediately available for everyday use while still being a useful experimental platform.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Additionally, the new kernel would be designed from the start to support multiple processor architectures, even allowing heterogeneous clusters to be constructed.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In order to bring the system up as quickly as possible, the system would be implemented by starting with the existing BSD code, and gradually re-implementing it as inter-process communication-based (IPC-based) programs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Thus Mach would begin as a monolithic system similar to existing UNIX systems, and progress toward the microkernel concept over time.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach started largely being an effort to produce a clearly defined, UNIX-based, highly portable Accent.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach developed on Accent's IPC concepts, but made the system much more UNIX-like in nature, making it possible to run UNIX programs with little or no modification.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] To do this, Mach introduced the port, representing each endpoint of a two-way IPC.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Ports had a concept of permissions like files under UNIX, permitting a very UNIX-like model of protection to be applied to them.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Additionally, Mach allowed any program to handle privileges that would normally be given to the operating system only, in order to permit user space programs to handle things such as controlling hardware.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Under Mach, and like UNIX, the operating system again becomes primarily a collection of utilities.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] As with UNIX, Mach keeps the concept of a driver for handling the hardware.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Therefore, all the drivers for the present hardware have to be included in the microkernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Other architectures based on hardware abstraction layer or exokernels could move the drivers out of the microkernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The main difference with UNIX is that instead of utilities handling files, they can handle any "task".
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] More operating system code was moved out of the kernel and into user space, resulting in a much smaller kernel and the rise of the term microkernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Unlike traditional systems, under Mach a process, or "task", can consist of a number of threads.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] While this is common in modern systems, Mach was the first system to define tasks and threads in this way.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The kernel's job was reduced from essentially being the operating system to running the "utilities" and providing them access to the hardware.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The existence of ports and the use of IPC is perhaps the most fundamental difference between Mach and traditional kernels.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Under UNIX, calling the kernel consists of an operation named a *system call* or *trap*.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The program uses a library to place data in a well known location in memory and then causes a *fault*, a type of error.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] When a system is first started, its kernel is set up to be the "handler" of all faults; thus, when a program causes a fault, the kernel takes over, examines the information passed to it, then carries out the instructions.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Under Mach, the IPC system was used for this role instead.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] To call system functionality, a program would ask the kernel for access to a port, then use the IPC system to send messages to that port.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Although sending a message requires a system call, just as a request for system functionality on other systems requires a system call, under Mach sending the message is pretty much all the kernel does; handling the actual request would be up to some other program.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Thread and concurrency support benefited by message passing with IPC mechanisms because tasks now consist of multiple code threads that Mach could freeze and unfreeze during message handling.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This permits the system to be distributed over multiple processors, either by using shared memory directly as in most Mach messages, or by adding code to copy the message to another processor if needed.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In a traditional kernel this is difficult to implement; the system has to be sure that different programs do not try to write to the same region of memory from different processors.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Using Mach ports makes this well defined and easy to implement, however, so Mach ports were made first-class citizens in that system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The IPC system initially had performance problems, so a few strategies were developed to improve performance.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Like its predecessor, Accent, Mach used a single shared-memory mechanism for physically passing the message from one program to another.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Physically copying the message would be too slow, so Mach relies on the machine's memory management unit (MMU) to quickly map the data from one program to another.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Only if the data is written to would it have to be physically copied, a process called "copy-on-write".
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Messages were also checked for validity by the kernel, to avoid bad data crashing one of the many programs making up the system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Ports were deliberately modeled on the UNIX file system concepts.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This permits the user to find ports using existing file system navigation concepts, as well as assigning rights and permissions as they would on the file system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Development under such a system would be easier.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Not only would the code being worked on exist in a traditional program that could be built using existing tools, it could also be started, debugged and killed off using the same tools.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] With a monokernel a bug in new code would take down the entire machine and require a reboot, whereas under Mach this would require only that the program be restarted.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Additionally the user could tailor the system to include, or exclude, whatever features they required.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Since the operating system was simply a collection of programs, they could add or remove parts by simply running or killing them as they would any other program.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Finally, under Mach, all of these features were deliberately designed to be extremely platform neutral.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Unlike UNIX, which was developed without regard for multiprocessing, Mach incorporates multiprocessing support throughout.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Its multiprocessing support is also exceedingly flexible, ranging from shared memory systems to systems with no memory shared between processors.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach is designed to run on computer systems ranging from one to thousands of processors.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In addition, Mach is easily ported to many varied computer architectures.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] A key goal of Mach is to be a distributed system capable of functioning on heterogeneous hardware.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] There are a number of disadvantages, however.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] A relatively mundane one is that it is not clear how to find ports.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Under UNIX this problem was solved over time as programmers agreed on a number of "well known" locations in the file system to serve various duties.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] While this same approach worked for Mach's ports as well, under Mach the operating system was assumed to be much more fluid, with ports appearing and disappearing all the time.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Without some mechanism to find ports and the services they represented, much of this flexibility would be lost.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach was initially hosted as additional code written directly into the existing 4.2BSD kernel, allowing the team to work on the system long before it was complete.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Work started with the already functional Accent IPC/port system, and moved on to the other key portions of the OS: tasks, threads, and virtual memory.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] As portions were completed various parts of the BSD system were re-written to call into Mach, and a change to 4.3BSD was also made during this process.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] By 1986 the system was complete to the point of being able to run on its own on the DEC VAX.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Although doing little of any practical value, the goal of making a microkernel was realized.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This was soon followed by versions on the IBM RT PC and for Sun Microsystems 68030-based workstations, proving the system's portability.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] By 1987 the list included the Encore Multimax and Sequent Balance machines, testing Mach's ability to run on multiprocessor systems.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] A public Release 1 was made that year, and Release 2 followed the next year.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Throughout this time the promise of a "true" microkernel had not yet been delivered.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] These early Mach versions included the majority of 4.3BSD in the kernel, a system known as a POE Server, resulting in a kernel that was actually larger than the UNIX it was based on.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The idea, however, was to move the UNIX layer out of the kernel into user-space, where it could be more easily worked on and even replaced outright.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Unfortunately performance proved to be a major problem, and a number of architectural changes were made in order to solve this problem.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Unwieldy UNIX licensing issues also plagued researchers, so this early effort to provide a non-licensed UNIX-like system environment continued to find use, well into the further development of Mach.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The resulting Mach 3 was released in 1990, and generated intense interest.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] A small team had built Mach and ported it to a number of platforms, including complex multiprocessor systems that were causing serious problems for older-style kernels.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This generated considerable interest in the commercial market, where a number of companies were considering changing hardware platforms.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] If the existing system could be ported to run on Mach, it seemed it would then be easy to change the platform underneath.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach received a major boost in visibility when the Open Software Foundation (OSF) announced they would be hosting future versions of OSF/1 on Mach 2.5, and were investigating Mach 3 as well.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach 2.5 was also selected for the NeXTSTEP system and a number of commercial multiprocessor vendors.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach 3 led to a number of efforts to port other operating systems parts for the microkernel, including IBM's Workplace OS and several efforts by Apple to build a cross-platform version of the classic Mac OS.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Support for running DOS applications in a Mach 3.0 environment was demonstrated by researchers, following on from earlier work running the classic Mac OS and MultiFinder under Mach 2.5.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] A research project at Digital Equipment Corporation investigated the feasibility of hosting OpenVMS on top of the Mach 3 kernel, and created a proof of concept with a subset of VMS' features.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach was originally intended to be a replacement for classical monolithic UNIX, and for this reason contained many UNIX-like ideas.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] For instance, Mach provided a permissions and security system similar to that used by UNIX's file system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Since the kernel was privileged (running in *kernel-space*) over other OS servers and software, it was possible for malfunctioning or malicious programs to send it commands that would cause damage to the system, and for this reason the kernel checked every message for validity.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Additionally most of the operating system functionality was to be located in user-space programs, so this meant there needed to be some way for the kernel to grant these programs additional privileges, e.g. to directly access hardware.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Some of Mach's more esoteric features were also based on this same IPC mechanism.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] For instance, Mach was able to support multi-processor machines with ease.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In a traditional kernel extensive work needs to be carried out to make it reentrant or *interruptible*, as programs running on different processors could call into the kernel at the same time.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Under Mach, the bits of the operating system are isolated in servers, which are able to run, like any other program, on any processor.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Although in theory the Mach kernel would also have to be reentrant, in practice this is not an issue because its response times are so fast it can simply wait and serve requests in turn.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach also included a server that could forward messages not just between programs, but even over the network, which was an area of intense development in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Unfortunately, the use of IPC for almost all tasks turned out to have serious performance impact.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Benchmarks on 1997 hardware showed that Mach 3.0-based UNIX single-server implementations were about 50% slower than native UNIX.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Study of the exact nature of the performance problems turned up a number of interesting facts.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] One was that the IPC was not the problem: there was some overhead associated with the memory mapping needed to support it, but this added only a small amount of time to making a call.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The rest, 80% of the time being spent, was due to additional tasks the kernel was running on the messages.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Primary among these was the port rights checking and message validity.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In benchmarks on an 486DX-50, a standard UNIX system call took an average of 21μs to complete, while the equivalent operation with Mach IPC averaged 114μs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Only 18μs of this was hardware related; the rest was the Mach kernel running various routines on the message.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Given a syscall that does nothing, a full round-trip under BSD would require about 40μs, whereas on a user-space Mach system it would take just under 500μs.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] When Mach was first being seriously used in the 2.x versions, performance was slower than traditional monolithic operating systems, perhaps as much as 25%.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This cost was not considered particularly worrying, however, because the system was also offering multi-processor support and easy portability.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Many felt this was an expected and acceptable cost to pay.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] When Mach 3 attempted to move most of the operating system into user-space, the overhead became higher still: benchmarks between Mach and Ultrix on a MIPS R3000 showed a performance hit as great as 67% on some workloads.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] For example, getting the system time involves an IPC call to the user-space server maintaining system clock.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The caller first traps into the kernel, causing a context switch and memory mapping.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The kernel then checks that the caller has required access rights and that the message is valid.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] If it is, there is another context switch and memory mapping to complete the call into the user-space server.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The process must then be repeated to return the results, adding up to a total of four context switches and memory mappings, plus two message verifications.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This overhead rapidly compounds with more complex services, where there are often code paths passing through many servers.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This was not the only source of performance problems.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Another centered on the problems of trying to handle memory properly when physical memory ran low and paging had to occur.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In the traditional monolithic operating systems, the authors had direct experience with which parts of the kernel called which others, allowing them to fine-tune their pager to avoid paging out code that was about to be used.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Under Mach this was not possible because the kernel had no real idea what the operating system consisted of.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Instead they had to use a single one-size-fits-all solution, which added to the performance problems.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach 3 attempted to address this problem by providing a simple pager, relying on user-space pagers for better specialization.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] But this turned out to have little effect.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In practice, any benefits it had were wiped out by the expensive IPC needed to call it in.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Other performance problems were related to Mach's support for multiprocessor systems.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] From the mid-1980s to the early 1990s, commodity CPUs grew in performance at a rate of about 60% a year, but the speed of memory access grew at only 7% a year.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This meant that the cost of accessing memory grew tremendously over this period, and since Mach was based on mapping memory around between programs, any "cache miss" made IPC calls slow.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] IPC overhead is a major issue for Mach 3 systems.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The concept of a *multi-server operating system* is still promising, though it still requires some research.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The developers have to be careful to isolate code into modules that do not call from server to server.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] For instance, the majority of the networking code would be placed in a single server, thereby minimizing IPC for normal networking tasks.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Most developers instead stuck with the original POE concept of a single large server providing the operating system functionality.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In order to ease development, they allowed the operating system server to run either in user-space or kernel-space.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This allowed them to develop in user-space and have all the advantages of the original Mach idea, and then move the debugged server into kernel-space in order to get better performance.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Several operating systems have since been constructed using this method, known as *co-location*, among them Lites, MkLinux, OSF/1, and NeXTSTEP/OPENSTEP/macOS.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The Chorus microkernel made this a feature of the basic system, allowing servers to be raised into the kernel space using built-in mechanisms.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach 4 attempted to address these problems with a more radical set of upgrades.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In particular, it was found that program code was typically not writable, so potential hits due to copy-on-write were rare.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Thus it made sense to not map the memory between programs for IPC, but instead migrate the program code being used into the local space of the program.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This led to the concept of "shuttles" and it seemed performance had improved, but the developers moved on with the system in a semi-usable state.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Mach 4 also introduced built-in co-location primitives, making it a part of the kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] By the mid-1990s, work on microkernel systems was largely stagnant, although the market had generally believed that all modern operating systems would be microkernel based by the 1990s.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The primary remaining widespread uses of the Mach kernel are Apple's macOS and its sibling iOS, which run atop a heavily modified hybrid Open Software Foundation Mach Kernel (OSFMK 7.3) called "XNU" also used in OSF/1.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Further analysis demonstrated that the IPC performance problem was not as obvious as it seemed.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Recall that a single-side of a syscall took 20μs under BSD and 114μs on Mach running on the same system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Of the 114, 11 were due to the context switch, identical to BSD.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] An additional 18 were used by the MMU to map the message between user-space and kernel space.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] This adds up to only 29μs, longer than a traditional syscall, but not by much.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The rest, the majority of the actual problem, was due to the kernel performing tasks such as checking the message for port access rights.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] While it would seem this is an important security concern, in fact, it only makes sense in a UNIX-like system.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] For instance, a single-user operating system running a cell phone or robot might not need any of these features, and this is exactly the sort of system where Mach's pick-and-choose operating system would be most valuable.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Likewise Mach caused problems when memory had been moved by the operating system, another task that only really makes sense if the system has more than one address space.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] DOS and the early Mac OS have a single large address space shared by all programs, so under these systems the mapping did not provide any benefits.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] These realizations led to a series of second generation microkernels, which further reduced the complexity of the system and placed almost all functionality in the user space.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] For instance, the L4 kernel (version 2) includes only seven system calls and uses 12k of memory, whereas Mach 3 includes about 140 functions and uses about 330k of memory.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] IPC calls under L4 on a 486DX-50 take only 5μs, faster than a UNIX syscall on the same system, and over 20 times as fast as Mach.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] Of course this ignores the fact that L4 is not handling permissioning or security; but by leaving this to the user-space programs, they can select as much or as little overhead as they require.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] The potential performance gains of L4 are tempered by the fact that the user-space applications will often have to provide many of the functions formerly supported by the kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] In order to test the end-to-end performance, MkLinux in co-located mode was compared with an L4 port running in user-space.
[src:macos-darwin/mach-kernel] L4 added about 5%–10% overhead, compared to Mach's 29%.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Mac OS X succeeded the classic Mac OS, the primary Macintosh operating system from 1984 to 2001.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Its underlying architecture came from NeXT's NeXTSTEP, as a result of Apple's acquisition of NeXT, which also brought Steve Jobs back to Apple.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The first desktop version, Mac OS X 10.0, was released on March 24, 2001.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apart from OS X Lion, all versions from Mac OS X Leopard onwards are UNIX 03 certified.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Each of Apple's other contemporary operating systems, including iOS, iPadOS, watchOS, tvOS, audioOS and visionOS, are derivatives of macOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] During its history, macOS has supported three major processor architectures: the initial version supported PowerPC-based Macs only, with support for Intel-based Macs beginning with OS X Tiger 10.4.4 and support for ARM-based Apple silicon Macs beginning with macOS Big Sur.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Support for PowerPC-based Macs was dropped with OS X Snow Leopard, and it was announced at the 2025 Worldwide Developers Conference that macOS Tahoe will be the last to support Intel-based Macs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Unlike versions of the classic Mac OS, Mac OS X retained the same major version number (10) for almost two decades, with major releases only incrementing the *minor* version number (e.g.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Since 2020, Apple increments the major version component in each major release, with macOS Big Sur getting version number 11.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2025, the numbering scheme was changed once again, now using the number of the year that follows the release year (e.g. macOS Tahoe, released in September 2025, has a version number 26).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] A prominent part of macOS's original brand identity was the use of the Roman numeral X, pronounced "ten", as well as code naming each release after species of big cats, and later, places within California.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple shortened the name to "OS X" in 2011 and then changed it to "macOS" in 2016 to align with the branding of Apple's other operating systems.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2020, macOS Big Sur was presented as version 11—a marked departure after 16 releases of macOS 10—but the naming convention continued to reference places within California.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2025, Apple unified the version number across all of its products to align with the year after their WWDC announcement, so the release announced at the 2025 WWDC, macOS Tahoe, is macOS 26.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The heritage of what would become macOS originated at NeXT, a company founded by Steve Jobs following his departure from Apple in 1985.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] There, the Unix-like NeXTSTEP operating system was developed, before being launched in 1989.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The kernel of NeXTSTEP is based upon the Mach kernel, which was originally developed at Carnegie Mellon University, with additional kernel layers and low-level user space code derived from parts of FreeBSD and other BSD operating systems.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Its graphical user interface was built on top of an object-oriented GUI toolkit using the Objective-C programming language.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Throughout the 1990s, Apple had tried to create a "next-generation" OS to succeed its classic Mac OS through the Taligent, Copland and Gershwin projects; however, all were eventually abandoned.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This led Apple to acquire NeXT in 1997, allowing NeXTSTEP, later called OPENSTEP, to serve as the basis for Apple's next-generation operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The acquisition also led to Steve Jobs returning to Apple as interim and later permanent CEO, shepherding the transformation of the programmer-friendly OPENSTEP into a system that would be adopted by Apple's primary market of home users and creative professionals.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The project was codenamed "Rhapsody" before being officially named Mac OS X.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The "X" in Mac OS X's name represents the Roman numeral for the number ten, and Apple has stated that it should be pronounced "ten" in this context; it is also commonly pronounced like the letter "X".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The iPhone X, iPhone XR and iPhone XS all later followed this convention.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The first version of Mac OS X, Mac OS X Server 1.0, was a transitional product, featuring an interface resembling the classic Mac OS, though it was not compatible with software designed for the older system; consumer releases of Mac OS X included more backward compatibility.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Mac OS applications could be rewritten to run natively via the Carbon API, with many alternatively able to be run directly through the Classic Environment albeit with a reduction in performance.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The consumer version of Mac OS X was launched in March 2001 with Mac OS X 10.0.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Reviews were variable, with many praising its sophisticated, glossy Aqua interface, but criticizing it for sluggish performance.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] With Apple's popularity at a low, the developer of FrameMaker, Adobe Inc., declined to develop new versions of it for Mac OS X.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] *Ars Technica* columnist John Siracusa, who reviewed every major OS X release up to 10.10, described the early releases in retrospect as "dog-slow, feature poor" and Aqua as "unbearably slow and a huge resource hog".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple rapidly developed several new releases of Mac OS X.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple released Mac OS X 10.1 in October 2001, delivering quality of life enhancements.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Beginning in January 2002, Apple preinstalled Mac OS X as the default operating system on all Macs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Later that year Apple released Mac OS X Jaguar (version 10.2), the first version to publicly use its code name in marketing and advertisements.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] As the operating system evolved, it moved away from the classic Mac OS, with applications being added and removed.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Considering music to be a key market, Apple developed the iPod music player and music software for the Mac, including iTunes and GarageBand.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Targeting the consumer and media markets, Apple emphasized its new "digital lifestyle" applications such as the iLife suite, integrated home entertainment through the Front Row media center and the Safari web browser.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] With the increasing popularity of the internet, Apple offered additional online services, including the .Mac, MobileMe, and later, iCloud products.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] It later began selling third-party applications through the Mac App Store.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Newer versions of Mac OS X also included modifications to the general interface, moving away from the striped gloss and transparency of the initial versions.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Some applications began to use a brushed metal appearance, or non-pinstriped title bar appearance in Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In Mac OS X Leopard (10.5), Apple announced a unification of the interface, with a standardized gray-gradient window style.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2006, the first Intel Macs were released with a specialized version of Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] A key development for the system was the announcement and release of the iPhone from 2007 onwards.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] While Apple's previous iPod media players used a minimal operating system, the iPhone used an operating system based on Mac OS X, which would later be called iPhone OS and then iOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The simultaneous release of two operating systems based on the same frameworks placed tension on Apple, which cited the iPhone as forcing it to delay Mac OS X Leopard.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] However, after Apple opened the iPhone to third-party developers, its commercial success drew attention to Mac OS X, with many iPhone software developers showing interest in Mac development.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2007, Mac OS X Leopard released with universal binary components, allowing installation on both Intel Macs and select PowerPC Macs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] It is also the final release with PowerPC Mac support.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2009, Mac OS X Snow Leopard (10.6) was the first version of Mac OS X to be built exclusively for Intel Macs and the final release with 32-bit Intel Mac support.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The name was intended to signal its status as an iteration of Leopard, focusing on technical and performance improvements rather than user-facing features; indeed it was explicitly branded to developers as being a 'no new features' release.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Since its release, several OS X or macOS releases (namely OS X Mountain Lion, OS X El Capitan, macOS High Sierra, and macOS Monterey) follow this pattern, with a name derived from its predecessor, similar to the 'tick–tock model' used by Intel.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Starting in 2011 with Mac OS X Lion (10.7) and OS X Mountain Lion (10.8), Apple moved some applications to a highly skeuomorphic style of design inspired by contemporary versions of iOS while simplifying some elements by making controls such as scroll bars fade out when not in use.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In addition, with Lion, Apple ceased to release separate server versions of Mac OS X, selling server tools as a separate downloadable application through the Mac App Store.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2012, with the release of OS X Mountain Lion, the name of the system was officially shortened from Mac OS X to OS X, after the previous version shortened the system name in a similar fashion a year prior.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] That year, Apple removed the head of OS X development, Scott Forstall, and design was changed towards a more minimal direction.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple's new user interface design, using deep color saturation, text-only buttons and a minimal, 'flat' interface, was debuted with iOS 7 in 2013.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] With OS X engineers reportedly working on iOS 7, the version released in 2013, OS X Mavericks (10.9), was something of a transitional release, with some of the skeuomorphic design removed, while most of the general interface of Mavericks remained unchanged.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The next version, OS X Yosemite (10.10), adopted a design similar to iOS 7 but with greater complexity suitable for an interface controlled with a mouse.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] From 2012 onwards, the system has shifted to an annual release schedule similar to that of Mac OS X releases prior to 10.4 Tiger.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] It also steadily cut the cost of updates from Snow Leopard onwards, before removing upgrade fees altogether in OS X Mavericks.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Some journalists and third-party software developers have suggested that this decision, while allowing more rapid feature release, meant less opportunity to focus on stability, with no version of OS X recommendable for users requiring stability and performance above new features.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple's 2015 update, OS X El Capitan (10.11), was announced to focus specifically on stability and performance improvements.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Its successor, macOS Mojave (10.14), was released in 2018, adding a dark mode option and a dynamic wallpaper setting.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] It was succeeded by macOS Catalina (10.15) in 2019, which replaces iTunes with separate apps for different types of media, and introduces the Catalyst system for porting iOS apps.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2020, Apple announced macOS Big Sur (version 11) at that year's WWDC.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This was the first increment in the primary version number of macOS since the release of Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000; updates to macOS Big Sur were given 11.x numbers, matching the version numbering scheme used by Apple's other operating systems.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Big Sur brought major changes to the user interface and was the first version to run on Apple Silicon, based on the ARM architecture.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The numbering system started with Big Sur continued in 2021 with macOS Monterey (12), 2022 with macOS Ventura (13), 2023 with macOS Sonoma (14), and 2024 with macOS Sequoia (15).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] During its Platforms State of the Union event on June 9, 2025, Apple announced that Tahoe would be the final version of macOS to operate on Intel-based Macs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2026, Apple announced macOS Golden Gate (version 27) at WWDC 2026.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] It will be the first version of macOS to run exclusively on Macs with Apple silicon and the last version with full Rosetta 2 functionality.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The Power Mac G5 had special Jaguar builds.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Tiger did not support 64-bit GUI applications, only 64-bit CLI applications.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] 32-bit (but not 64-bit) PowerPC applications were supported on Intel processors with Rosetta.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] 64-bit Intel applications are supported on Apple silicon Macs with Rosetta 2.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] However, Intel-based Macs are unable to run ARM-based applications, such as iOS and iPadOS apps.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] At macOS's core is a POSIX-compliant operating system built on top of the XNU kernel, (which incorporated large parts of FreeBSD kernel) and FreeBSD userland for the standard Unix facilities available from the command line interface.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple has released this family of software as a free and open source operating system named Darwin.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] On top of Darwin, Apple layered a number of components, including the Aqua interface and the Finder, to complete the GUI-based operating system which is macOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] With its original introduction as Mac OS X, the system brought a number of new capabilities to provide a more stable and reliable platform than its predecessor, the classic Mac OS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] For example, pre-emptive multitasking and memory protection improved the system's ability to run multiple applications simultaneously without them interrupting or corrupting each other.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Many aspects of macOS's architecture are derived from OPENSTEP, which was designed to be portable, to ease the transition from one platform to another.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] For example, NeXTSTEP was ported from the original 68k-based NeXT workstations to x86 and other architectures before NeXT was purchased by Apple, and OPENSTEP was later ported to the PowerPC architecture as part of the Rhapsody project.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Prior to macOS High Sierra, and on drives other than solid state drives (SSDs), the default file system is HFS+, which it inherited from the classic Mac OS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Operating system designer Linus Torvalds had criticized HFS+, saying it is "probably the worst file system ever", whose design is "actively corrupting user data".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] He criticized the case insensitivity of file names, a design made worse when Apple extended the file system to support Unicode.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The Darwin subsystem in macOS manages the file system, which includes the Unix permissions layer.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Later, another Macworld editor, Dan Frakes, called the procedure of repairing permissions vastly overused.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] He argues that macOS typically handles permissions properly without user interference, and resetting permissions should only be tried when problems emerge.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The architecture of macOS incorporates a layered design: the layered frameworks aid rapid development of applications by providing existing code for common tasks.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple provides its own software development tools, most prominently an integrated development environment called Xcode.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Xcode provides interfaces to compilers that support several programming languages including C, C++, Objective-C, and Swift.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] For the Mac transition to Intel processors, it was modified so that developers could build their applications as a universal binary, which provides compatibility with both the Intel-based and PowerPC-based Macintosh lines.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] First and third-party applications can be controlled programmatically using the AppleScript framework, retained from the classic Mac OS, or using the newer Automator application that offers pre-written tasks that do not require programming knowledge.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple offered two main APIs to develop software natively for macOS: Cocoa and Carbon.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Cocoa was a descendant of APIs inherited from OPENSTEP with no ancestry from the classic Mac OS, while Carbon was an adaptation of classic Mac OS APIs, allowing Mac software to be minimally rewritten to run natively on Mac OS X.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The Cocoa API was created as the result of a 1993 collaboration between NeXT Computer and Sun Microsystems.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This heritage is highly visible for Cocoa developers, since the "NS" prefix is ubiquitous in the framework, standing variously for **N**eXT**S**TEP or **N**eXT/**S**un.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The official OPENSTEP API, published in September 1994, was the first to split the API between Foundation and ApplicationKit and the first to use the "NS" prefix.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Traditionally, Cocoa programs have been mostly written in Objective-C, with Java as an alternative.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Since 2014, Apple has promoted its new programming language Swift as the preferred language for software development on Apple platforms.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple's original plan with macOS was to require all developers to rewrite their software into the Cocoa APIs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This caused much outcry among existing Mac developers, who threatened to abandon the platform rather than invest in a costly rewrite, and the idea was shelved.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] To permit a smooth transition from Mac OS 9 to Mac OS X, the Carbon Application Programming Interface (API) was created.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Applications written with Carbon were initially able to run natively on both classic Mac OS and Mac OS X, although this ability was later dropped as Mac OS X developed.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Carbon was not included in the first product sold as Mac OS X: the little-used original release of Mac OS X Server 1.0, which also did not include the Aqua interface.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple limited further development of Carbon from the release of Leopard onwards and announced that Carbon applications would not run at 64-bit.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] A number of macOS applications continued to use Carbon for some time afterwards, especially ones with heritage dating back to the classic Mac OS and for which updates would be difficult, uneconomic or not necessary.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This included Microsoft Office up to Office 2016, and Photoshop up to CS5.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Early versions of macOS could also run some classic Mac OS applications through the Classic Environment with performance limitations; this feature was removed from 10.5 onwards and all Macs using Intel processors.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Because macOS is POSIX compliant, many software packages written for the other Unix-like systems including Linux can be recompiled to run on it, including many scientific and technical programs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Third-party projects such as Homebrew, Fink, MacPorts and pkgsrc provide pre-compiled or pre-formatted packages.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple and others have provided versions of the X Window System graphical interface which can allow these applications to run with an approximation of the macOS look-and-feel.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The current Apple-endorsed method is the open-source XQuartz project; earlier versions could use the X11 application provided by Apple, or before that the XDarwin project.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apps installed through the Mac App Store run within a sandbox, restricting their ability to exchange information with other applications or modify the core operating system and its features.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This has been cited as an advantage, by allowing users to install apps with confidence that they should not be able to damage their system, but also as a disadvantage due to blocking the Mac App Store's use for professional applications that require elevated privileges.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Applications without any code signature cannot be run by default except from a computer's administrator account.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Some are included with macOS and some sold separately.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This includes iWork, Final Cut Pro, Logic Pro, iLife, and the database application FileMaker.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Numerous other developers also offer software for macOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2018, Apple introduced an application layer, codenamed Marzipan, to port iOS apps to macOS. macOS Mojave included ports of four first-party iOS apps including Home and News, and it was announced that the API would be available for third-party developers to use from 2019.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] With macOS Catalina in 2019, the application layer was made available to third-party developers as Mac Catalyst.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Tools such as XPostFacto and patches applied to the installation media have been developed by third parties to enable installation of newer versions of macOS on systems not officially supported by Apple.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Except for features requiring specific hardware such as graphics acceleration or DVD writing, the operating system offers the same functionality on all supported hardware.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] As most Mac hardware components, or components similar to those, since the Intel transition are available for purchase, some technology-capable groups have developed software to install macOS on non-Apple computers.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] These are referred to as Hackintoshes, a portmanteau of the words "hack" and "Macintosh".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This violates Apple's EULA (and is therefore unsupported by Apple technical support, warranties etc.), but communities that cater to personal users, who do not install for resale and profit, have generally been ignored by Apple.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] These self-made computers allow more flexibility and customization of hardware, but at a cost of leaving the user more responsible for their own machine, such as on matter of data integrity or security.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Psystar, a business that attempted to profit from selling macOS on non-Apple certified hardware, was sued by Apple in 2008.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In April 2002, eWeek announced a rumor that Apple had a version of Mac OS X code-named Marklar, which ran on Intel x86 processors.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The idea behind Marklar was to keep Mac OS X running on an alternative platform should Apple become dissatisfied with the progress of the PowerPC platform.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] These rumors subsided until late in May 2005, when various media outlets, such as *The Wall Street Journal* and CNET, announced that Apple would unveil Marklar in the coming months.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] On June 6, 2005, Steve Jobs announced in his keynote address at WWDC that Apple would be making the transition from PowerPC to Intel processors over the following two years, and that Mac OS X would support both platforms during the transition.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Jobs also confirmed rumors that Apple had versions of Mac OS X running on Intel processors for most of its developmental life.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Intel-based Macs would run a new recompiled version of OS X along with Rosetta, a binary translation layer which enables software compiled for PowerPC Mac OS X to run on Intel Mac OS X machines.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The system was included with Mac OS X versions up to version 10.6.8.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple dropped support for Classic mode on the new Intel Macs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Third party emulation software such as Mini vMac, Basilisk II and SheepShaver provided support for some early versions of Mac OS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] A new version of Xcode and the underlying command-line compilers supported building universal binaries that would run on either architecture.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] PowerPC-only software is supported with Apple's official binary translation software, Rosetta, though applications eventually had to be rewritten to run properly on the newer versions released for Intel processors.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple initially encouraged developers to produce universal binaries with support for both PowerPC and Intel.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] PowerPC binaries suffer a performance penalty when run on Intel Macs through Rosetta.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Moreover, some PowerPC software, such as kernel extensions and System Preferences plugins, are not supported on Intel Macs at all.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Plugins for Safari need to be compiled for the same platform as Safari, so when Safari is running on Intel, it requires plug-ins that have been compiled as Intel-only or universal binaries, so PowerPC-only plug-ins will not work.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] While Intel Macs can run PowerPC, Intel, and universal binaries, PowerPC Macs support only universal and PowerPC builds.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Support for the PowerPC platform was dropped following the transition.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2009, Apple announced at WWDC that Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard would drop support for PowerPC processors and be Intel-only.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Rosetta continued to be offered as an optional download or installation choice in Snow Leopard before it was discontinued with Mac OS X 10.7 Lion.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In addition, new versions of Mac OS X first- and third-party software increasingly required Intel processors, including new versions of iLife, iWork, Aperture and Logic Pro.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Rumors of Apple shifting Macs from Intel to in-house ARM processors used by iOS devices began circulating as early as 2011, and ebbed and flowed throughout the 2010s.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Rumors intensified in 2020, when numerous reports announced that the company would announce its shift to its custom processors at WWDC.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple officially announced its shift to processors designed in-house on June 22, 2020, at WWDC 2020, with the transition planned to last for approximately two years.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The first release of macOS to support ARM was macOS Big Sur.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Big Sur and later versions support Universal 2 binaries, which are applications consisting of both Intel (x86-64) and Apple silicon (AArch64) binaries; when launched, only the appropriate binary is run.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Additionally, Intel binaries can be run on Apple silicon-based Macs using the Rosetta 2 binary translation software.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The transition was completed at WWDC 2023 with the announcement of the Apple silicon Mac Pro, ending the transition in 3 years, slightly behind schedule.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The change in processor architecture allows Macs with ARM processors to be able to run iOS and iPadOS apps natively.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The macOS user interface places a menu bar along the top edge of the screen, containing the Apple menu and application menus at the start, and status menus at the end.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The Dock is placed along the bottom of the screen by default, and contains icons for pinned and active applications, file and folder shortcuts, minimized windows, and the Trash (or Bin).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] On most windows, the start of the title bar has three buttons resembling a horizontal traffic light, which respectively close, minimize, and resize the window.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple has continued to change aspects of the macOS appearance and design, particularly with tweaks to the appearance of windows and the menu bar.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Since 2012, Apple has sold almost all of its Mac models with high-resolution Retina displays, and macOS and its APIs have extensive support for resolution-independent development on supporting high-resolution displays.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Reviewers have described Apple's support for the technology as superior to that on Windows.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The human interface guidelines published by Apple for macOS are followed by many applications, giving them consistent user interface and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Services available in every Cocoa application include spelling and grammar checkers, special characters palette, color picker, font chooser and dictionary.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The graphics system OpenGL composites windows onto the screen to allow hardware-accelerated drawing.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] This technology, introduced in version 10.2, is called Quartz Extreme, a component of Quartz.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Quartz's internal imaging model correlates well with the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, making it easy to output PDF to multiple devices.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] As a side result, PDF viewing and creating PDF documents from any application are built-in features.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Reflecting its popularity with design users, macOS also has system support for a variety of professional video and image formats and includes an extensive pre-installed font library, featuring many prominent brand-name designs.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] A major addition between the classic Mac OS and the first major release of Mac OS X was Aqua, a design language with water-like elements.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Every window element, text, graphic, or widget was drawn on-screen using spatial anti-aliasing technology.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The preexisting ColorSync technology was improved and built into the core drawing engine, to provide color matching for printing and multimedia professionals.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Drop shadows were added around windows and isolated text elements to provide a sense of depth.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] New interface elements were integrated, including sheets (dialog boxes attached to specific windows) and drawers, which would slide out and provide options.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The use of soft edges, translucent colors, and pinstripes, similar to the hardware design of the first iMacs, brought more texture and color to the user interface when compared to what Mac OS 9 and Mac OS X Server 1.0's Platinum appearance had offered.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Third-party developers started producing skins for customizable applications and other operating systems which mimicked the Aqua appearance.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] To some extent, Apple has used the successful transition to this design as leverage, at various times threatening legal action against people who make or distribute software with an interface the company says is derived from its copyrighted design.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Following a similar design change in iOS 7, OS X Yosemite shifted to a flat design language, simplifying many of the Aqua elements and icons.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In 2025, macOS Tahoe adopted the Liquid Glass design language, which was inspired in part by Aqua.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The Finder is a file browser allowing quick access to all areas of the computer, which has been modified throughout subsequent releases of macOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Quick Look has been part of the Finder since version 10.5.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] It allows for dynamic previews of files, including videos and multi-page documents without opening any other applications.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Spotlight, a file searching technology which has been integrated into the Finder since version 10.4, allows rapid real-time searches of data files; mail messages; photos; and other information based on item properties (metadata) or content.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple added Exposé in version 10.3 (called Mission Control since version 10.7), a feature which includes three functions to help accessibility between windows and desktop.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Its functions are to instantly reveal all open windows as thumbnails for easy navigation to different tasks, display all open windows as thumbnails from the current application, and hide all windows to access the desktop.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] FileVault is optional encryption of the user's files with the 128-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES-128).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Sync Services allows applications to access a centralized extensible database for various elements of user data, including calendar and contact items.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] The operating system then managed conflicting edits and data consistency.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple has developed support for emoji characters by including the proprietary Apple Color Emoji font.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple has also connected macOS with social networks such as Twitter and Facebook through the addition of share buttons for content such as pictures and text.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Apple has brought several applications and features that originally debuted in iOS, its mobile operating system, to macOS, notably the intelligent personal assistant Siri, which was introduced in version 10.12 of macOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] There are 47 system languages available in macOS for the user at the moment of installation; the system language is used throughout the entire operating system environment.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Input methods for typing in dozens of scripts can be chosen independently of the system language.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Updates have added increased support for Chinese characters and interconnections with popular social networks in China.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] macOS can be updated using the Software Update settings pane in System Settings or the `softwareupdate` command line utility.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Until OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion, a separate Software Update application performed this functionality.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In Mountain Lion and later, this was merged into the Mac App Store application, although the underlying update mechanism remains unchanged and is fundamentally different from the download mechanism used when purchasing an App Store application.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] In macOS 10.14 Mojave, the updating function was moved again to the Software Update settings pane.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] Most Macs receive six or seven years of macOS updates.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p01] After a new major release of macOS, the previous two releases still receive occasional updates, but many security vulnerabilities are only patched in the latest macOS release.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mac OS X versions were named after big cats, with the exception of Mac OS X Server 1.0 and the original public beta, from Mac OS X 10.0 until OS X 10.9 Mavericks, when Apple switched to using California locations.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Prior to its release, version 10.0 was code named internally at Apple as "Cheetah", and Mac OS X 10.1 was code named internally as "Puma".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] After the immense buzz surrounding Mac OS X 10.2, codenamed "Jaguar", Apple's product marketing began openly using the code names to promote the operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.3 was marketed as "Panther", Mac OS X 10.4 as "Tiger", Mac OS X 10.5 as "Leopard", Mac OS X 10.6 as "Snow Leopard", Mac OS X 10.7 as "Lion", OS X 10.8 as "Mountain Lion", and OS X 10.9 as "Mavericks".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] "Panther", "Tiger" and "Leopard" are registered as trademarks of Apple, but "Cheetah", "Puma" and "Jaguar" have never been registered.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple has also registered "Lynx" and "Cougar" as trademarks, though these were allowed to lapse.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Computer retailer Tiger Direct sued Apple for its use of the name "Tiger".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] On May 16, 2005, a US federal court in the Southern District of Florida ruled that Apple's use did not infringe on Tiger Direct's trademark.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] On September 13, 2000, Apple released a US$29.95 "preview" version of Mac OS X, internally codenamed Kodiak, to gain feedback from users.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The "PB", as it was known, marked the first public availability of the Aqua interface and Apple made many changes to the UI based on customer feedback.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mac OS X Public Beta expired and ceased to function in Spring 2001.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] On March 24, 2001, Apple released Mac OS X 10.0 (internally codenamed Cheetah).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The initial version was slow, incomplete, and had very few applications available at launch, mostly from independent developers.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] While many critics suggested that the operating system was not ready for mainstream adoption, they recognized the importance of its initial launch as a base on which to improve.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Simply releasing Mac OS X was received by the Macintosh community as a great accomplishment, for attempts to overhaul the Mac OS had been underway since 1996, and had been delayed by countless setbacks.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Later that year, on September 25, 2001, Mac OS X 10.1 (internally codenamed Puma) was released.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It featured increased performance and provided missing features, such as DVD playback.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple released 10.1 as a free upgrade CD for 10.0 users, in addition to the $129 boxed version for people running Mac OS 9.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It was discovered that the upgrade CDs were full install CDs that could be used with Mac OS 9 systems by removing a specific file; Apple later re-released the CDs in an actual stripped-down format that did not facilitate installation on such systems.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] On January 7, 2002, Apple announced that Mac OS X was to be the default operating system for all Macintosh products by the end of that month.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] On August 23, 2002, Apple followed up with Mac OS X 10.2 Jaguar, the first release to use its code name as part of the branding.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It brought significant performance improvements, and an updated version of Aqua's visual design.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The Happy Mac icon — which had appeared during the Mac OS startup sequence since the original Macintosh — was replaced with a gray Apple logo.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mac OS X v10.3 Panther was released on October 24, 2003.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It significantly improved performance and incorporated the most extensive update yet to the user interface.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Support for some early G3 computers such as "beige" Power Macs and "WallStreet" PowerBooks was discontinued.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.4 Tiger was released on April 29, 2005.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple stated that Tiger contained more than 200 new features.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] As with Panther, certain older machines were no longer supported; Tiger requires a Mac with 256 MB of RAM and a built-in FireWire port.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Among the new features, Tiger introduced Spotlight, Dashboard, Smart Folders, updated Mail program with Smart Mailboxes, QuickTime 7, Safari 2, Automator, VoiceOver, Core Image and Core Video.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The initial release of the Apple TV used a modified version of Tiger with a different graphical interface and fewer applications and services.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] On January 10, 2006, Apple released the first Intel-based Macs along with the 10.4.4 update to Tiger.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] This operating system functioned identically on the PowerPC-based Macs and the new Intel-based machines, with the exception of the Intel release lacking support for the Classic environment.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard was released on October 26, 2007.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It was called by Apple "the largest update of Mac OS X".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Leopard supports both PowerPC- and Intel x86-based Macintosh computers; support for the G3 processor was dropped and the G4 processor required a minimum clock rate of 867 MHz, and at least 512 MB of RAM to be installed.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The single DVD works for all supported Macs (including 64-bit machines).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] New features include a new look, an updated Finder, Time Machine, Spaces, Boot Camp pre-installed, full support for 64-bit applications (including graphical applications), new features in Mail and iChat, and a number of new security features.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Leopard is an Open Brand UNIX 03 registered product on the Intel platform.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It was also the first BSD-based OS to receive UNIX 03 certification.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Leopard dropped support for the Classic Environment and all Classic applications.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It was the final version of Mac OS X to support the PowerPC architecture.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard was released on August 28, 2009.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Rather than delivering big changes to the appearance and end user functionality like the previous releases of Mac OS X, Snow Leopard focused on "under the hood" changes, increasing the performance, efficiency, and stability of the operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Snow Leopard only supported machines with Intel CPUs, required at least 1 GB of RAM, and dropped default support for applications built for the PowerPC architecture (Rosetta could be installed as an additional component to retain support for PowerPC-only applications).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Snow Leopard also featured new 64-bit technology capable of supporting greater amounts of RAM, improved support for multi-core processors through Grand Central Dispatch, and advanced GPU performance with OpenCL.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The 10.6.6 update also introduced support for the Mac App Store, Apple's digital distribution platform for macOS applications.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] OS X 10.7 Lion was released on July 20, 2011.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It brought developments made in Apple's iOS, such as an easily navigable display of installed applications called Launchpad and a greater use of multi-touch gestures, to the Mac.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] This release removed Rosetta, making it incompatible with PowerPC applications.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Changes made to the GUI include auto-hiding scrollbars that only appear when they are used, and Mission Control which unifies Exposé, Spaces, Dashboard, and full-screen applications within a single interface.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple also made changes to applications: they resume in the same state as they were before they were closed, similar to iOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion was released on July 25, 2012.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Following the release of Lion the previous year, it was the first of the annual rather than two-yearly updates to OS X (and later macOS), which also closely aligned with the annual iOS operating system updates.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It incorporates some features seen in iOS 5, which include Game Center, support for iMessage in the new Messages messaging application, and Reminders as a to-do list app separate from iCal (which is renamed as Calendar, like the iOS app).
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It also includes support for storing iWork documents in iCloud.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Notification Center, which makes its debut in Mountain Lion, is a desktop version similar to the one in iOS 5.0 and higher.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Application pop-ups are now concentrated on the corner of the screen, and the Center itself is pulled from the right side of the screen.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mountain Lion also includes more Chinese features including support for Baidu as an option for Safari search engine, QQ, 163.com and 126.com services for Mail, Contacts and Calendar, Youku, Tudou and Sina Weibo are integrated into share sheets.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Starting with Mountain Lion, Apple software updates (including the OS) are distributed via the App Store.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] This updating mechanism replaced the Apple Software Update utility.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] OS X 10.9 Mavericks was released on October 22, 2013.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It is a free upgrade to all users running Snow Leopard or later with a 64-bit Intel processor.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Its changes include the addition of the previously iOS-only Maps and iBooks applications, improvements to the Notification Center, enhancements to several applications, and many under-the-hood improvements.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] OS X 10.10 Yosemite was released on October 16, 2014.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It features a redesigned user interface similar to that of iOS 7, intended to feature a more minimal, text-based 'flat' design, with use of translucency effects and intensely saturated colors.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple's showcase new feature in Yosemite is Handoff, which enables users with iPhones running iOS 8.1 or later to answer phone calls, receive and send SMS messages, and complete unfinished iPhone emails on their Mac.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] As of OS X 10.10.3, Photos replaced iPhoto and Aperture.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] OS X 10.11 El Capitan was released on September 30, 2015.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Similar to Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard, Apple described this release as emphasizing "refinements to the Mac experience" and "improvements to system performance".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Refinements include public transport built into the Maps application, GUI improvements to the Notes application, adopting San Francisco as the system font for clearer legibility, and the introduction of System Integrity Protection.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The Metal API, first introduced in iOS 8, was also included in this operating system for "all Macs since 2012".
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] According to Apple, Metal accelerates system-level rendering by up to 50 percent, resulting in faster graphics performance for everyday apps.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Metal also delivers up to 10 times faster draw call performance for more fluid experience in games and pro apps.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS 10.12 Sierra was released to the public on September 20, 2016.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] New features include the addition of Siri, optimized storage, and updates to Photos, Messages, and iTunes.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS 10.13 High Sierra was released to the public on September 25, 2017.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Like OS X El Capitan and OS X Mountain Lion, High Sierra is a refinement-based update having very few new features visible to the user, including updates to Safari, Photos, and Mail, among other changes.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The major change under the hood is the switch to the Apple File System, optimized for the solid-state storage used in most new Mac computers.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS 10.14 Mojave was released on September 24, 2018.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The update introduced a system-wide dark mode and several new apps lifted from iOS, such as Apple News.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It was the first version to require a GPU that supports Metal.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mojave also changed the system software update mechanism from the App Store (where it had been since OS X Mountain Lion) to a new panel in System Preferences.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS 10.15 Catalina was released on October 7, 2019.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Updates included enhanced voice control, and bundled apps for music, video, and podcasts that together replace the functions of iTunes, and the ability to use an iPad as an external monitor.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Catalina officially dropped support for 32-bit applications.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS Big Sur was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 22, 2020, and it was made available to the general public on November 12, 2020.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] This is the first time the major version number of the operating system has been incremented since the Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It brings Arm support, new icons, and aesthetic user interface changes to the system.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS Ventura was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 6, 2022 and released on October 24, 2022.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It came with the redesigned System Preferences (named System Settings) to a more iOS-like design, and the new Freeform, Weather and Clock apps that run natively on Mac.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Users can use an iPhone as a webcam for video conferencing with Continuity Camera.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Siri's appearance was changed to look more like the versions on iOS 14 and iPadOS 14.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Mail introduced schedule send and undo send for emails, and Message also got the ability to undo send and edit messages.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Stage Manager was introduced as a new way to organize all open windows in a desktop.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Maps gained the feature for multiple-stop routes, Metal 3 was added with support for spatial and temporal image upscaling, Lockdown Mode was added to reduce the risk of a cyberattack, and the ability to play ambient background sounds was added as an accessibility feature in System Settings.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS Sonoma was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 5, 2023, and released on September 26, 2023. macOS Sonoma revamped widgets—they can now be placed anywhere on the desktop.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Game mode optimizes game performance by prioritizing gaming tasks and allocating more GPU and CPU capacity to the game, and by doing so is able to provide smoother frame rates for gameplay.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The Spotlight Search bar and all app icons were made even more rounded, smoother animations were implemented for notifications and the lock screen, and new slow-motion screensavers of different locations worldwide were added.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] When logged in, they gradually slow down and become the desktop wallpaper.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS Sequoia was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 10, 2024.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS Tahoe was announced on June 9, 2025, during the WWDC 2025 keynote address.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It is the first macOS version to feature the new Liquid Glass design introduced across Apple operating systems that year.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It is also the first macOS to use Apple's new release number convention, which gives all of Apple's operating systems the same version number.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS Golden Gate was announced at WWDC on June 8, 2026.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] It introduces visual intelligence, redesigns Siri, and brings Apple Intelligence features to apps such as Safari and Passwords.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Golden Gate also improves Liquid Glass on windows and sidebars, and allows users to adjust the system opacity.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple publishes Apple Platform Security documents to lay out the security protections built into macOS and Mac hardware.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] These prevent some vulnerabilities within macOS.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Only the latest major release of macOS (macOS Tahoe as of June 2026) receives patches for all known security vulnerabilities.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] The previous two releases receive some security updates, but not for all vulnerabilities known to Apple.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] macOS Ventura added support for Rapid Security Response (RSR) updates and Lockdown Mode.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Rapid Security Response updates may require a reboot, but take less than a minute to install.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] In an analysis, Hackintosh developer Mykola Grymalyuk noted that RSR updates can only fix userland vulnerabilities, and cannot patch the macOS kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Lockdown Mode is an optional security feature designed to provide extreme protection for users who may be at risk of targeted cyberattacks, such as journalists, activists, and public figures.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] This mode significantly alters the functionality of the device to enhance security against sophisticated threats, particularly from spyware and state-sponsored attacks.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple says most people are never impacted by these attacks.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] In its earlier years, Mac OS X enjoyed a near-absence of the types of malware and spyware that have affected Microsoft Windows users. macOS has a smaller usage share compared to Windows.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Worms, as well as potential vulnerabilities, were noted in 2006, which led some industry analysts and anti-virus companies to issue warnings that Apple's Mac OS X is not immune to malware.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Increasing market share coincided with additional reports of a variety of attacks.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] In early 2011, Mac OS X experienced a large increase in malware attacks, and malware such as Mac Defender, MacProtector, and MacGuard was seen as an increasing problem for Mac users.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] At first, the malware installer required the user to enter the administrative password, but later versions installed without user input.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Initially, Apple support staff were instructed not to assist in the removal of the malware or admit the existence of the malware issue, but as the malware spread, a support document was issued.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple announced an OS X update to fix the problem.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] An estimated 100,000 users were affected.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] Apple releases security updates for macOS regularly, as well as signature files containing malware signatures for Xprotect, an anti-malware feature part of File Quarantine present since Mac OS X Snow Leopard.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] As of January 2023, macOS is the second-most widely used general-purpose desktop operating system used on the World Wide Web following Microsoft Windows, with a 15.33% usage share, according to statistics compiled by StatCounter.
[src:macos-darwin/macos-p02] As a device company, Apple has mostly promoted macOS to sell Macs, with promotion of macOS updates focused on existing users, promotion at Apple Store and other retail partners, or through events for developers.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] XNU was originally developed by NeXT for the NeXTSTEP operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] After Apple acquired NeXT, the kernel was updated with code derived from OSF MK 7.3 from OSF, and the FreeBSD project, and the DriverKit was replaced with new API on a restricted subset of C++ (based on Embedded C++) named IOKit.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] macOS achieved UNIX certification in 2007 with the release of Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard under the Single UNIX Specification (SUS) by The Open Group.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Despite this, Apple retained the original 'XNU' name, which stands for 'X is Not Unix,' a relic from its NeXTSTEP origins before macOS was UNIX-certified.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] This has led to confusion, as the name suggests that XNU is separate from UNIX, even though macOS, as a whole, is officially recognized as a UNIX operating system.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] XNU is a hybrid kernel, containing features of both monolithic kernels and microkernels.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] As of June 2026, XNU runs on ARM64 and x86-64 processors.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] PowerPC support was removed as of the Mac OS X Snow Leopard kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Support for IA-32 was removed as of the Mac OS X Lion kernel; support for 32-bit ARM was removed as of iOS 11.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] The basis of the XNU kernel is a heavily modified (hybrid) Open Software Foundation Mach kernel (OSF MK) 7.3.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] OSF MK 7.3 is a microkernel that includes applicable code from the University of Utah Mach 4 kernel and from the many Mach 3.0 variants forked from the original Carnegie Mellon University Mach 3.0 microkernel.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] XNU doesn't use Mach as a microkernel, rather including other subsystems (such as the BSD one) as a part of the kernel, instead of as a userspace daemons.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Mach in XNU is used to manage virtual memory, facilitate Inter-process communication (IPC), and do Input/output (I/O) operations with the console.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Apple licensed OSF MK 7.3 from the OSF, and attempted to streamline some tasks by building BSD functions into the kernel along with the Mach code.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] The result is a heavily modified (hybrid) OSF MK 7.3 kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] The BSD code present in XNU has been most recently synchronised with that from the FreeBSD kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Although much of it has been significantly modified, code sharing still occurs between Apple and the FreeBSD Project as of 2009.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] The first thing that happens after Mach initializes BSD is the initialization of memory allocation.*Amit Singh.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Archived from the original on April 19, 2019.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] XNU in Mac OS X Snow Leopard, v10.6, (Darwin version 10) comes in two varieties, a 32-bit version called *K32* and a 64-bit version called *K64*.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] K32 can run 64-bit applications in userland.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] What was new in Mac OS X 10.6 was the ability to run XNU in 64-bit kernel space.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] K32 was the default kernel for 10.6 *Server* when used on all machines except Mac Pro and Xserve models from 2008 onwards and can run 64-bit applications.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Booting while holding down *6* and *4* forces the machine to boot K64 on machines supporting 64-bit kernels.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] K64 will run 32-bit applications but it will not run 32-bit kernel extensions (KEXTs), so these must be ported to K64 to be able to load.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] XNU in OS X Mountain Lion (10.8) and later only provides a 64-bit kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] IOKit is the device driver framework, written in a subset of C++ based on Embedded C++ that lacks lacks features such as exceptions, multiple inheritance, and templates.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Using its object-oriented design, features common to any class of driver are provided within the framework, helping device drivers be written in less time and code.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] IOKit is multi-threaded, symmetric multiprocessing (SMP)-safe, and allows for hot-pluggable devices and automatic, dynamic device configuration.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Many drivers can be written to run in user mode, which further enhances the stability of the system.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] If a driver running in user mode crashes, it will not crash the kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] However, if a driver running in kernel mode crashes it will crash the kernel.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] Examples of drivers running in kernel mode include disk adapter and network adapter drivers, graphics drivers, drivers for Universal Serial Bus (USB) and FireWire host controllers, and drivers for virtual machine software such as VirtualBox, Parallels Desktop for Mac, and VMware Fusion.
[src:macos-darwin/xnu] In macOS Catalina and later releases, DriverKit allows some of those types of drivers to run in user mode.
